@node P1 "Editor's Corner"
@toc "menu"

Editor's Corner             by @{"Lori Vinciguerra" link P6}

Well, it's summer now!  All of you educators are probably going to start
planning courses and projects for the fall semester soon.  While you are
relaxing and planning, try to check out at least one of the Amiga shows
which are happening in Canada this summer. You can get full descriptions
and information in the "New Products and Exciting News" section of this
issue. Things on the development front seemed to be a little slow during
the Commodore liquidation.  Now that the new Amiga Technologies section
of ESCOM is beginning to get into gear, I'm anticipating product
development to pick up.  If any of you are writing educational products
and want them announced in this newsletter, just send me a note.  I
always check the newsgroup comp.sys.amiga.announce to see if there's
anything of interest.

As for ESCOM, there have been some very positive statements made about
the Amiga's future.  I am confident that our platform will be around for
a long time and that the user base will grow.  I am very anxious to see
what will happen in the educational market.  At least the Amiga is a
viable contender again.  As you plan your fall projects be sure to slip
an Amiga demo in somewhere.  There is a lot of free software on Aminet
to do cool things in all areas of education.  Be sure to check out
Ralph's article on using the Internet and the World Wide Web to find
what you are looking for.

Thanks to Jason Compton for printing my article on "Advice for ESCOM
in the Educational Market" in an issue of Amiga Report.  I received
a lot of email from all of the world telling me about schools which
are using our favorite machine.  I also received some interesting
stories about what they are being used for.  I hope to be able to
include these stories and more in a future issue.

The deadline for article submissions for the October issue is September
15, 1995.  If any of your students are interested in writing an
article, please pass on this information.  As always, email your
article to owl@davinci.reading.ma.us or use U.S. mail to send to OWL
Software, 460 Summer Ave., Reading, MA 01867-3819.  Have a great summer!


