News on the Internet and WWW for Amigans         by @{"Ralph Vinciguerra" link P8}


The World Wide Web (WWW) continues to demonstrate its excellent potential
for use in education. A growing number of sites with educational information
are making the use of a connection to the web more enlightening every day. A
good example is the new central web entry point for NASA (the U.S. National
Aeronautics and Space and Administration), "http://www.nasa.gov/". From this
entry point one can obtain information on current and upcoming missions as
well as general NASA information.

There continue to be two main Amiga entry points on the World Wide Web which
index Amiga resources: The Amiga Home Page and The Amiga Web Directory. The
Amiga Home Page has recently moved to a new URL:
"http://www.omnipresence.com/Amiga/". The Amiga Web page remains at the URL
"http://www.prairienet.org/community/clubs/cucug/amiga.html".

A new AmiNet mirror is online at this URL: "http://www.netnet.net/aminet/"
It is also accessible by ftp to "ftp.netnet.com". This helps make up for the
recent disappearance of the Amiga section of the www.cdrom.com AmiNet
mirror. Since it's new, its response time is quite good for people in North
America.

A new Amiga online magazine: Amiga Link is available at this URL:
"http://www.omnipresence.com/Amiga/News/ALink/", joining numerous other
Amiga online journals including Amiga Report, and Amiga Report Tech
Magazine.

The software for connecting our Amigas to the WWW continues to improve.
Currently at OWL we are using a combination of AmiTCP4.0, PPPV1.30
registered, and ALynx1.11. This combination allows text-mode WWW traversal
with the ability to display sound and image links by launching additional
programs, once we dialup to an internet service provider. Most pieces you'll
need can be downloaded from AmiNet. AmiTCP and PPP are somewhat challenging
to install, and require detailed information from your internet provider
along with careful attention to their installation instructions. Perhaps at
some point we'll have an Amiga WWW Kit which has all the needed pieces
together with a good installer script.

Alynx is currently up to version 1.24 and can be found at this URL:
"http://www.fhi-berlin.mpg.de/amiga/alynx.html".

We currently do not use the other popular Amiga Web browser, AMosaic, since
it does not run well on our networked A2000 with AmigaDOS 2.04 and does not
support Web forms. Web forms allow providers to create interactive fill-in
forms through the Web browsers. ALynx does support forms in acceptable
manner, however, things are looking up for AMosaic, as the new beta version
is undergoing testing now, and supports forms along with a more robust
implementation. Very nice work by a dedicated group of volunteer Amiga
developers! We expect to purchase AmigaDOS 3.1 (3.2?) from Amiga
Technologies as soon as possible in order to support this new version. The
URL for AMosaic is "http://www.omnipresence.com/amosaic/2.0/".

Good luck in your net surfing!



